    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-07-12T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-07-12T14:00:00-05:00" n="587"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d587">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.182/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gallman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-07-12T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 12, 1926—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. Department’s 20, September 20, 1923, 6 p.m. and Legation’s 46, September 27,
                    1923, 9 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d587fn1">Neither printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The United States would be pleased now to enter upon negotiations with Costa Rica
                    for a treaty of friendship, commerce and consular rights similar to the treaty
                    signed on December 8, 1923 by the United States and Germany<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d587fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1923v02#pg_22">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 22</ref>.</note> (treaty series No.
                    725), and the treaty signed February 22, 1926, between the United States and
                        Salvador.<note n="3" xml:id="d587fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1926v02#pg_912">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1926, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                            p. 912</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In September, 1923, the Government of Costa Rica was favorable toward entering
                    into such negotiations. Ascertain and telegraph Department whether they are now
                        favorable.<note n="4" xml:id="d587fn4">Negotiations were suspended while the
                        Senate had under consideration the treaty signed with Germany.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In regard to commercial provisions the principle embodied in the draft treaty to
                    be submitted by the United States would be unconditional most-favored-nation
                    treatment. Should Costa Rica find it agreeable to enter into negotiations, the
                    Department will send you a draft of the treaty with instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
